If two systems preserve the same function or the same constraint through different mechanisms, they don’t have to remember identically.

A glacier “remembers” climate differently than DNA remembers evolution.

DNA “remembers” differently than the immune system.

The immune system “remembers” differently than a person.

A person “remembers” differently than a library.

A library “remembers” differently than a culture.

The mechanisms are different.

The continuity is different.

Yet each carries some aspect of the past into the future.

That’s why I kept trying to separate the mechanisms—not to diminish the idea, but because I think it’s actually richer when we recognize there isn’t one universal kind of memory.

